# Spec: Record Layouts (Fingerprint minutiae & Face images) and Reference Documents

Summary
- This document specifies the record field layouts the generator must implement for fingerprints (ISO/IEC 19794-2 style minutiae templates and ISO/IEC 19794-4 image fields) and faces (ISO/IEC 19794-5 face image container).
- It also lists authoritative reference documents and what I verified about each (where I was able to open or observe content publicly).

A. What we are implementing (high-level mapping)
1) Fingerprint minutiae record (ISO/IEC 19794-2 style — JSON mapping)
- Top-level header fields
  - RecordFormatIdentifier: textual ID (e.g., "FMR" / numeric format id)
  - Version: ISO version string (e.g., "19794-2:2011")
  - CaptureDeviceID (optional)
  - CaptureTime (ISO 8601)
  - SubjectID / SampleID
  - FingerPosition (enumeration: left_index, right_thumb, etc.)
  - ImpressionType (live-scan, rolled, latent, etc.)
  - ImageWidth, ImageHeight, ResolutionDPI (if image-backed)
  - MinutiaeCount
- Per-minutia entry (array of objects)
  - x: integer (pixel coordinate, 0..width-1)
  - y: integer (pixel coordinate, 0..height-1)
  - angle_deg: float or integer (degrees; 0 <= angle < 360)
  - type: enum ["ending","bifurcation", ...] (ISO uses numeric codes; map to readable names)
  - quality: optional integer (0-100)
- Optional extended fields
  - RidgeCounts: list of ridge-count items between minutiae pairs (if implemented)
  - Core and Delta coordinates (if synthesized)
- Notes:
  - The ISO standard defines compact and card formats and exact binary encodings (byte sizes, endianness). The JSON mapping must document correspondence to those binary fields (e.g., x/y -> 2‑byte unsigned ints, angle -> 1 byte in 0..255 range if binary).

2) Fingerprint image metadata (ISO/IEC 19794-4 style — JSON mapping)
- Header fields:
  - ImageType (plain, rolled, partial)
  - Width, Height (pixels)
  - Resolution (dpi)
  - ColorSpace (GRAY / YUV / RGB)
  - Compression (none / JPEG / WSQ / JPEG2000)
  - ImageData: filename or base64 blob
- Notes:
  - For passport-like contexts, JPEG2000 is commonly used for high-quality images.

3) Face image record (ISO/IEC 19794-5 style — JSON mapping)
- Top-level header:
  - Version (e.g., "19794-5:2011")
  - ImageType (still, controlled, uncontrolled)
  - Width, Height (pixels)
  - ColorSpace (RGB/YUV)
  - Compression (JPEG / JPEG2000)
  - CaptureDevice, CaptureTime, SubjectID
- Face-specific fields:
  - FaceBoundingBox: {x, y, width, height}
  - Landmarks: { left_eye: {x,y}, right_eye: {x,y}, nose_tip: {x,y}, mouth_left: {x,y}, mouth_right: {x,y} } (ISO allows multiple landmark sets and richer annotations)
  - Pose: yaw, pitch, roll (degrees; optional)
  - QualityScores: overallFaceQuality, occlusion, illumination (optional)
  - ImageData: filename or base64 blob
- Notes:
  - ISO/IEC 19794-5 describes a container holding one or more face image blocks and associated metadata; in passports (ICAO DG2) a face image block typically wraps a single high-quality image (JPEG/JPEG2000) and may include annotations.

B. Field-level guidance and mapping to ISO words
- Where ISO uses numeric codes or compact binary fields, provide a one-to-one mapping table in the implementation docs:
  - e.g., ISO minutia type codes -> string tokens; angle encoding ranges -> degrees in JSON.
- For binary emulation: document expected byte-length and endianness for each header field (e.g., record header = 4-byte ASCII "FMR\0", 4-byte version, 2-byte minutiaeCount, then minutiae entries each N bytes).

C. Reference documents (existence verification)
Below I list the reference documents and the verification I was able to perform (public evidence / links I inspected):

1. ISO/IEC 19794-2 — "Biometric data interchange formats — Part 2: Finger minutiae data"
   - Verified content / evidence:
     - Relaton/metadata entries available on GitHub that reference ISO/IEC 19794-2:2011 and link to IEC webstore preview:
       - https://github.com/relaton/relaton-data-iec/blob/6b98fb61c33c958640dea963f264cc86834eee97/data/iso_iec_19794-2_2011.yaml
       - That relaton entry contains links to: https://webstore.iec.ch/publication/10792 and a preview link: https://webstore.iec.ch/preview/info_isoiec19794-2{ed2.0}en.pdf
     - Public project references showing practical usage/implementations and examples:
       - Open-source projects reference ISO templates and show example header handling:
         - OpenAFIS README referencing ISO/IEC 19794-2:2005: https://github.com/neilharan/openafis/blob/3ae1c757c6dafea977a33ef51380e37f1715e626/README.md#L65-L140
         - FingerJetFXOSE headers reference ISO/IEC output formats: https://github.com/FingerJetFXOSE/FingerJetFXOSE/blob/1726ba08bf7f2137d2f861ac1ae124d5cd355eee/FingerJetFXOSE/libFJFX/include/FJFX.h#L25-L101
     - Conclusion: the ISO/IEC 19794-2 standard exists and public metadata/previews and multiple open-source projects reference and implement its format. The relaton YAML points to the official webstore preview.

2. ISO/IEC 19794-5 — "Biometric data interchange formats — Part 5: Face image data"
   - Verified content / evidence:
     - Public codebases and commits referencing ISO/IEC 19794-5 and its usage for DG2/ICAO face image containers:
       - Example commit and docs referencing ISO/IEC 19794-5 in a DG2/DG1 parsing project: https://github.com/iland112/local-pkd/commit/3dcd85c00268940e4dd899c02d14e1fc7cc7c8e9
       - Project documentation and parsers (public repos) reference "ISO/IEC 19794-5 (Face image container)" when implementing DG2 parsing.
     - Relaton / standards catalogs typically list 19794-5 as part of the 19794 series; authoritative purchase/preview is available through ISO/IEC webstores (search "ISO/IEC 19794-5" on iso.org / iec.ch).
     - Conclusion: ISO/IEC 19794-5 is a published standard and is referenced broadly; authoritative copies are distributed via the ISO and IEC webstores and via standards catalogues. Public projects reference it for face image handling (DG2).

3. ICAO Doc 9303 (Machine-Readable Travel Documents) — DG2 usage (face image in ePassports)
   - Verified content / evidence:
     - ICAO Doc 9303 is the authoritative specification for ePassports and references ISO/IEC 19794 for biometric payloads (DG2 face). The ICAO publication page:
       - https://www.icao.int/publications/pages/publication.aspx?docnum=9303
     - Multiple projects and parsers implement DG1/DG2 parsing using ISO/IEC 19794-5 as the face image container; see DG1/DG2 parsing discussions in public repos (example above).
     - Conclusion: ICAO 9303 exists and is the normative document governing passport chip DG structure; obtain official copy from ICAO.

4. Other supporting materials / examples
   - NIST/NBIS and FBI formats are often used in practice for fingerprints; open-source implementations and libraries (e.g., NBIS, OpenAFIS) demonstrate practical encodings and conversions.

Caveats about "opening" the official ISO docs
- Official ISO/IEC standards (full normative text) are typically sold/licensed and not freely downloadable in full from the ISO webstore. Preview pages and metadata (via relaton or webstore preview) are publicly accessible and I inspected those metadata entries and repository references as evidence of existence and structure. For full, authoritative normative text and exact binary field encodings, obtain the official ISO/IEC documents (purchase or licensed access).

D. Implementation notes & fidelity targets
- Target fidelity:
  - JSON mapping: high fidelity — include every ISO-referenced logical field (header values, per-minutia fields, face-region annotations) and document their binary equivalents.
  - Binary emulation: support a minimal, documented binary layout that mirrors ISO field ordering (for testing ingestion pipelines that expect FMR-like headers). If project requires full, byte-level conformance, note that the team must obtain the ISO standard PDF and run an exact conformance implementation as a follow-up task.
- Example mapping decisions (practical):
  - Angle encoding: represent angles in JSON as degrees float; document that binary ISO may encode them as 0..255 mapping to 0..360° (implementation must document mapping).
  - Minutia coordinates: JSON = integer pixels (0..W-1), binary = 2-byte unsigned.
  - Face images: prefer embedding JPEG (or JPEG2000 for passport-style test vectors); include image magic checks in validator.

E. Useful public references (places to acquire/verify standards)
- IEC / ISO webstores (purchase/preview pages) — use search for exact part numbers:
  - IEC preview found via relaton metadata for 19794-2: https://webstore.iec.ch/preview/info_isoiec19794-2{ed2.0}en.pdf
  - ISO/IEC 19794-5: search on ISO webstore or IEC webstore for the face part.
- GitHub references (implementation examples and parsers):
  - Relaton dataset entry for 19794-2: https://github.com/relaton/relaton-data-iec/blob/6b98fb61c33c958640dea963f264cc86834eee97/data/iso_iec_19794-2_2011.yaml
  - OpenAFIS README (example usage referencing ISO minutiae templates): https://github.com/neilharan/openafis/blob/3ae1c757c6dafea977a33ef51380e37f1715e626/README.md#L65-L140
  - FingerJetFXOSE header comments referencing ISO outputs: https://github.com/FingerJetFXOSE/FingerJetFXOSE/blob/1726ba08bf7f2137d2f861ac1ae124d5cd355eee/FingerJetFXOSE/libFJFX/include/FJFX.h#L25-L101
  - DG2 parser commit referencing ISO/IEC 19794-5 and ICAO DG2 handling: https://github.com/iland112/local-pkd/commit/3dcd85c00268940e4dd899c02d14e1fc7cc7c8e9

F. Recommended approach when implementing exact binary conformance
- Obtain the ISO/IEC part PDFs (19794-2 and 19794-5) from the ISO or IEC webstore and implement a parser that matches the byte-level field sizes and encodings described in the normative text.
- Run interoperability tests with existing open-source tooling (e.g., NBIS utilities or libraries that claim ISO compatibility) and with small official test vectors if available.

